WEBVTT

1
00:00:08.510 --> 00:00:10.077
<i>TAD:</i>
<i>Jay. Mark.</i>

2
00:00:10.177 --> 00:00:11.746
I would like to discuss with you

3
00:00:11.846 --> 00:00:14.716
my vision for Mountains
of the Valley. the world's

4
00:00:14.816 --> 00:00:17.050
first upscale breastaurant.

5
00:00:17.150 --> 00:00:18.586
I'm confused. Trevor.

6
00:00:18.686 --> 00:00:20.053
I thought you owned
the trademark to that name

7
00:00:20.153 --> 00:00:21.523
and you had refused
to sell it to him.

8
00:00:21.623 --> 00:00:24.424
Yes. but in the end.
Jay couldn't countenance

9
00:00:24.526 --> 00:00:26.961
the alternative name
that Tad settled upon:

10
00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:28.428
Boobs and Steaks.

11
00:00:28.530 --> 00:00:30.297
So they asked me to let Tad

12
00:00:30.397 --> 00:00:32.266
have "Mountains of the Valley."

13
00:00:32.366 --> 00:00:34.134
-and here we are.
-TAD: And how are we coming

14
00:00:34.234 --> 00:00:36.103
with the menu. Jay?
You got my email about the lamb?

15
00:00:36.203 --> 00:00:37.137
Yeah. I did.

16
00:00:37.237 --> 00:00:38.640
Tad. it's just. you know.

17
00:00:38.740 --> 00:00:41.108
the individual chops
are kind of my signature.

18
00:00:41.208 --> 00:00:43.912
Yeah. got to be a rack.
otherwise it won't make sense

19
00:00:44.012 --> 00:00:45.379
when the servers ask

20
00:00:45.479 --> 00:00:46.748
if anyone would like to see
their huge rack.

21
00:00:46.848 --> 00:00:48.583
Well. it's hard
to argue with that. Tad.

22
00:00:48.683 --> 00:00:51.886
And what exactly
are jalapeño knockers?

23
00:00:51.986 --> 00:00:53.453
That's for Jay to figure out.

24
00:00:53.555 --> 00:00:55.523
But they're on the menu.

25
00:00:57.025 --> 00:00:59.894
(sighs) Gabe. we have
to find a way to save Mahesh.

26
00:00:59.994 --> 00:01:01.963
We can't let our restaurant
turn into this.

27
00:01:02.062 --> 00:01:04.064
Okay. guys.
I'll see you tomorrow.

28
00:01:04.164 --> 00:01:05.767
(short chuckle)

29
00:01:07.401 --> 00:01:08.402
Yeah. this is hell.

30
00:01:08.503 --> 00:01:10.137
Who is that?

31
00:01:10.237 --> 00:01:12.907
Nikki. the new barkeep.

32
00:01:13.007 --> 00:01:14.809
She looks...

33
00:01:14.909 --> 00:01:16.176
very qualified.

34
00:01:16.578 --> 00:01:18.445
Are you talking about
those strong muddling hands?

35
00:01:18.546 --> 00:01:20.147
Yeah. I noticed that. too.

36
00:01:20.247 --> 00:01:22.082
Calluses for days. am I right?

37
00:01:22.182 --> 00:01:24.619
Oh. yeah. No mint is safe.

38
00:01:26.420 --> 00:01:28.455
♪ ♪

39
00:01:31.425 --> 00:01:33.828
What do you mean.
you're moving out?

40
00:01:33.928 --> 00:01:35.329
I know this comes as a shock.

41
00:01:35.429 --> 00:01:37.331
When I moved to the
basement. I considered it

42
00:01:37.431 --> 00:01:39.667
a permanent
and authentic decision.

43
00:01:39.767 --> 00:01:42.102
But what can I say?
My friends miss me.

44
00:01:42.202 --> 00:01:44.271
(scoffs) Spare us. Isaac.

45
00:01:44.371 --> 00:01:47.107
You moved down here so you could
run for ghost representative

46
00:01:47.207 --> 00:01:48.676
as a basement dweller.

47
00:01:48.776 --> 00:01:50.044
Now you don't need us.

48
00:01:50.143 --> 00:01:52.013
so you're out of here. Fine.

49
00:01:52.112 --> 00:01:55.349
Take your carpet
and put it in your bag

50
00:01:55.449 --> 00:01:57.351
-and shove it.
-Oh.

51
00:01:57.451 --> 00:02:01.188
Well. this is emotional
for all of us. Hmm?

52
00:02:01.288 --> 00:02:05.225
I. for one. will remember each
and every one of you fondly.

53
00:02:05.325 --> 00:02:08.796
I'm back. (laughs)
I'm free of those freaks.

54
00:02:08.896 --> 00:02:11.666
(sniffs) Oh. do you smell that?

55
00:02:11.766 --> 00:02:13.735
-I don't smell anything.
-Precisely.

56
00:02:13.835 --> 00:02:15.536
Oh. it's good to be home.

57
00:02:15.637 --> 00:02:17.005
Welcome back. Isaac.

58
00:02:18.673 --> 00:02:20.140
<i>SAMANTHA: Hey.</i>

59
00:02:20.407 --> 00:02:22.644
uh. Tad? I just wanted
to talk to you about something.

60
00:02:22.744 --> 00:02:25.379
Oh. I'm glad you're here.

61
00:02:25.479 --> 00:02:27.048
What if instead of
small. medium and large.

62
00:02:27.147 --> 00:02:28.181
we offered our drinks

63
00:02:28.281 --> 00:02:30.018
in a B cup. C cup and D cup?

64
00:02:30.118 --> 00:02:31.753
I think this guy
might be a genius.

65
00:02:31.853 --> 00:02:34.221
Tad. are you sure
that this rebrand

66
00:02:34.321 --> 00:02:36.024
is the best thing
for the business?

67
00:02:36.124 --> 00:02:38.559
It's just. Mahesh
is very precious to Jay.

68
00:02:38.660 --> 00:02:40.561
I mean.
he named it after his dad.

69
00:02:40.662 --> 00:02:42.897
I named the main character
after my dad

70
00:02:42.997 --> 00:02:46.000
in my classic noir film
<i>Jimmy The Deadbeat.</i>

71
00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:48.435
-He must have been very touched.
-(phone chimes)

72
00:02:48.536 --> 00:02:50.337
Sons of bitches. Sorry. sorry.

73
00:02:50.437 --> 00:02:53.041
City council is voting tomorrow

74
00:02:53.141 --> 00:02:55.677
to officially
remove me from office.

75
00:02:55.777 --> 00:02:57.512
Oh. I thought
that already happened.

76
00:02:57.612 --> 00:03:00.915
Effectively. yeah.
It's just a formality.

77
00:03:01.015 --> 00:03:03.084
But if the vote
goes your way tomorrow.

78
00:03:03.183 --> 00:03:04.619
you could be mayor again?

79
00:03:04.719 --> 00:03:06.888
Never gonna happen.
Councilman Gus Heyward.

80
00:03:06.988 --> 00:03:08.188
my nemesis.

81
00:03:08.288 --> 00:03:09.691
is the deciding vote.

82
00:03:09.791 --> 00:03:12.225
so unless he has
a miraculous change of heart.

83
00:03:12.325 --> 00:03:14.327
I'm afraid you guys
are stuck with me.

84
00:03:14.428 --> 00:03:15.863
I always wanted
to have a nemesis.

85
00:03:15.963 --> 00:03:17.197
Well. what about your friend
who was sleeping

86
00:03:17.297 --> 00:03:18.465
with your wife
for all those years?

87
00:03:18.566 --> 00:03:20.267
Oh. yeah.
I guess I do have one.

88
00:03:20.367 --> 00:03:21.736
-(chuckles)
-SAMANTHA: Hang on.

89
00:03:21.836 --> 00:03:24.404
if Gus did change his mind
and reinstate you.

90
00:03:24.505 --> 00:03:26.107
is that something
you'd be interested in?

91
00:03:26.206 --> 00:03:27.407
Yeah. of course.

92
00:03:27.508 --> 00:03:29.911
Public service is my passion.

93
00:03:30.011 --> 00:03:32.146
I just want to help people
and make the world better.

94
00:03:32.245 --> 00:03:34.281
Hey. Tad.
the tank tops came in but

95
00:03:34.381 --> 00:03:35.783
they're not bedazzled
like you wanted.

96
00:03:35.883 --> 00:03:37.250
TAD:
Seriously?

97
00:03:37.518 --> 00:03:40.121
I spent 20 minutes
on the phone with that guy.

98
00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:41.455
I sent him multiple sketches.

99
00:03:41.556 --> 00:03:43.591
Sorry. excuse me.

100
00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:46.694
This is interesting.

101
00:03:47.028 --> 00:03:48.663
Sam. it seems like
if you can get Tad

102
00:03:48.763 --> 00:03:50.565
his mayorship back. he'll
drop the whole restaurant idea.

103
00:03:50.665 --> 00:03:52.967
Whoa. ho. let's just
take a beat.

104
00:03:53.067 --> 00:03:55.103
What about Nikki?
She just got this job.

105
00:03:55.203 --> 00:03:56.470
Is anybody thinking about her?

106
00:03:56.571 --> 00:03:58.139
'Cause I'm thinking about her.

107
00:03:58.238 --> 00:04:00.074
I'm... I'm thinking
about her quite a bit.

108
00:04:00.174 --> 00:04:01.341
SAMANTHA:
We got to talk to this
councilman.

109
00:04:01.441 --> 00:04:03.276
see if we can change his mind.

110
00:04:03.376 --> 00:04:05.179
Now. hold your horses.
You want to flip a politician.

111
00:04:05.278 --> 00:04:07.181
-you're gonna
need some leverage.
-What do you mean?

112
00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:09.349
I'm talking about dirt.

113
00:04:09.449 --> 00:04:11.351
Who is this guy?
What's he hiding?

114
00:04:11.451 --> 00:04:13.621
Everybody has something
they don't want someone

115
00:04:13.721 --> 00:04:16.157
-to know.
-Like my unpermitted deck.

116
00:04:16.256 --> 00:04:17.257
I mean. I would've
done just about anything

117
00:04:17.357 --> 00:04:18.793
to keep that from coming out.

118
00:04:18.893 --> 00:04:21.929
The stairs weren't even
to code. God forgive me.

119
00:04:22.029 --> 00:04:23.531
That makes a lot of sense. Joan.

120
00:04:23.631 --> 00:04:24.932
I'm gonna go do some digging
on this councilman.

121
00:04:25.032 --> 00:04:26.299
see if we can
find anything useful.

122
00:04:28.268 --> 00:04:30.805
It's like she doesn't care
about Nikki at all.

123
00:04:30.905 --> 00:04:32.272
(scoffs)
Heartless.

124
00:04:37.111 --> 00:04:38.146
(groans)

125
00:04:39.947 --> 00:04:40.915
(groans)

126
00:04:42.449 --> 00:04:44.018
Isaac!

127
00:04:44.118 --> 00:04:45.620
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

128
00:04:46.721 --> 00:04:48.956
I just can't seem
to fall asleep.

129
00:04:49.056 --> 00:04:51.659
Perhaps I'm out of practice
sleeping lying down.

130
00:04:51.759 --> 00:04:53.728
In the basement.
we sleep standing up.

131
00:04:53.828 --> 00:04:55.863
Like cattle. Or horses.

132
00:04:55.963 --> 00:04:57.865
Also. giraffes.
Which. as I understand them.

133
00:04:57.965 --> 00:05:01.002
are kind of like
tall. orange donkeys.

134
00:05:01.102 --> 00:05:02.503
Look. I've got
a big day tomorrow.

135
00:05:02.603 --> 00:05:03.871
The new <i>People</i> magazine
is arriving.

136
00:05:03.971 --> 00:05:04.972
and I'm hoping
for a Chalamet cover.

137
00:05:05.239 --> 00:05:06.741
Oh. Wait.
what happened to Momoa?

138
00:05:06.841 --> 00:05:09.911
Oh. hunks are over. It's
all about hot rodent men now.

139
00:05:10.011 --> 00:05:11.913
"Hot rodent men."

140
00:05:12.013 --> 00:05:13.581
Okay. good night.

141
00:05:16.617 --> 00:05:18.186
(groans)

142
00:05:18.286 --> 00:05:20.588
I swear to God.

143
00:05:20.688 --> 00:05:23.191
<i>JOAN:</i>
<i>Oh. God. this takes me back.</i>

144
00:05:23.291 --> 00:05:25.358
digging up dirt on a bigwig.

145
00:05:25.458 --> 00:05:27.562
A politician with a dark past.

146
00:05:27.662 --> 00:05:30.164
Classic noir stuff.

147
00:05:30.264 --> 00:05:32.600
This guy's a saint.
Councilman Gus Heyward

148
00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:33.901
volunteers at church.

149
00:05:34.001 --> 00:05:35.402
fundraises
for the Salvation Army.

150
00:05:35.503 --> 00:05:37.104
fosters disabled dogs.

151
00:05:37.205 --> 00:05:40.541
Boom. I got
a parking ticket in 1996.

152
00:05:40.641 --> 00:05:42.109
Is that anything?

153
00:05:42.210 --> 00:05:44.745
Not exactly a dead hooker.
but it's a start.

154
00:05:44.846 --> 00:05:46.614
Happy blackmailing. everyone.
How's it going?

155
00:05:46.714 --> 00:05:48.415
JOAN:
We've got bubkes.

156
00:05:48.516 --> 00:05:49.884
This guy's cleaner
than Orson Welles' plate

157
00:05:49.984 --> 00:05:51.652
after a steak dinner at Musso's.

158
00:05:51.752 --> 00:05:52.954
She has a way with words.

159
00:05:53.054 --> 00:05:54.088
I don't know
what any of them mean.

160
00:05:54.188 --> 00:05:55.957
but I like how she says 'em.

161
00:05:56.057 --> 00:05:57.357
Wait. is that the guy?

162
00:05:57.457 --> 00:05:58.960
-That's Gus?
-SAMANTHA: Yeah.

163
00:05:59.060 --> 00:06:01.428
-Why?
-Because I've seen him before.

164
00:06:01.529 --> 00:06:02.730
And if we need dirt.

165
00:06:02.830 --> 00:06:04.599
oh. boy. I got
a whole truckload.

166
00:06:04.699 --> 00:06:06.100
Enough to get the mayor
his job back?

167
00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:07.602
And then some.

168
00:06:07.702 --> 00:06:09.436
Oh! I got
a second parking ticket.

169
00:06:09.537 --> 00:06:10.905
A pattern emerges.

170
00:06:17.011 --> 00:06:18.312
Just tell us. Pete.
What do you have on Gus

171
00:06:18.411 --> 00:06:19.780
that would be so damning
that he would have

172
00:06:19.881 --> 00:06:21.782
to reinstate Tad as the mayor?

173
00:06:21.883 --> 00:06:23.150
Well. I will tell you

174
00:06:23.251 --> 00:06:25.353
right after a patented
Martino drumroll.

175
00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:34.829
-I saw him in an orgy.
-Oh.

176
00:06:34.929 --> 00:06:36.429
-What?
-You remember months ago

177
00:06:36.530 --> 00:06:38.132
when we snuck into
the Farnsbys' media room

178
00:06:38.232 --> 00:06:39.634
to move that bookshelf
so that Thor

179
00:06:39.734 --> 00:06:40.801
could watch his son get married?

180
00:06:40.902 --> 00:06:42.336
We do have fun.

181
00:06:42.435 --> 00:06:44.138
Yes. I remember.
I jumped out the window

182
00:06:44.238 --> 00:06:46.674
and I ran home to cancel our
Ever Creek water subscription.

183
00:06:46.774 --> 00:06:49.810
Well. after you left. you'll
recall Jay was stuck in a closet

184
00:06:49.911 --> 00:06:51.812
while your friends. who
were renting the Farnsbys' home.

185
00:06:51.913 --> 00:06:55.316
put on a DVD of what they
thought was the movie <i>Swingers.</i>

186
00:06:55.415 --> 00:06:57.285
But it turned out
to be a sex tape

187
00:06:57.385 --> 00:06:59.120
of people who
actually were swingers.

188
00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:00.388
Bingo.

189
00:07:00.755 --> 00:07:02.990
a septuagenarian orgy.
one of the stars of which

190
00:07:03.090 --> 00:07:04.457
was our friend Gus right here.

191
00:07:04.558 --> 00:07:05.860
-Oh.
-Oh.

192
00:07:06.193 --> 00:07:08.362
Jay. Gus was in that amateur
porn video you heard

193
00:07:08.461 --> 00:07:09.997
in the Farnsbys' closet.

194
00:07:10.097 --> 00:07:11.632
Oh. God.

195
00:07:11.732 --> 00:07:14.467
That haunting knee clicking?
That was Gus's.

196
00:07:14.568 --> 00:07:16.671
A click. a clack.
a romp in the sack.

197
00:07:16.771 --> 00:07:19.040
She can really sell
some gibberish.

198
00:07:19.140 --> 00:07:20.341
But. babe.
none of this is good to us

199
00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:21.642
unless we can get
some hard evidence.

200
00:07:21.742 --> 00:07:23.044
no pun intended.

201
00:07:23.144 --> 00:07:24.145
Yes.

202
00:07:24.245 --> 00:07:26.113
My guy's not afraid to go blue.

203
00:07:26.213 --> 00:07:27.882
Well. we better get that tape.

204
00:07:27.982 --> 00:07:30.685
Or we could accept
that Mahesh had a good run.

205
00:07:30.785 --> 00:07:32.153
and Nikki gets to keep her job.

206
00:07:32.253 --> 00:07:35.189
Who are we to play God?

207
00:07:35.289 --> 00:07:36.524
So we'll get the tape.

208
00:07:36.624 --> 00:07:37.692
-Yeah. we'll get the tape.
-Great.

209
00:07:38.059 --> 00:07:41.529
Suddenly. Ward McAllister
opens his mouth

210
00:07:41.629 --> 00:07:46.200
and vomits all over
Alva Vanderbilt's birthday cake.

211
00:07:46.300 --> 00:07:48.636
Oh. and that's when I realize

212
00:07:48.736 --> 00:07:51.105
-the clams have turned.
-(yawns)

213
00:07:52.306 --> 00:07:53.808
Am I boring you?

214
00:07:53.908 --> 00:07:56.844
I'm sorry. Hetty. I-I didn't get
a wink last night.

215
00:07:56.944 --> 00:07:58.045
I've been
in the basement so long.

216
00:07:58.145 --> 00:07:59.313
I think I've grown habituated

217
00:07:59.413 --> 00:08:02.350
to their
unusual nocturnal customs.

218
00:08:02.450 --> 00:08:03.483
HETTY:
Hmm.

219
00:08:03.584 --> 00:08:05.519
You've been institutionalized.

220
00:08:05.619 --> 00:08:07.188
Excuse me?

221
00:08:07.288 --> 00:08:08.923
In 1876. my mother made
an offhand comment.

222
00:08:09.023 --> 00:08:10.558
admitting to feelings
of sexual longing.

223
00:08:10.658 --> 00:08:12.860
She was thus
diagnosed with hysteria

224
00:08:12.960 --> 00:08:15.096
and whisked away
to the local asylum.

225
00:08:15.196 --> 00:08:17.398
-Naturally.
-Upon her return
18 months later.

226
00:08:17.497 --> 00:08:19.400
she had grown accustomed
to the ways of the asylum.

227
00:08:19.499 --> 00:08:21.669
and it was now home where
she felt a strange unease.

228
00:08:21.769 --> 00:08:22.703
Yes.

229
00:08:22.803 --> 00:08:24.538
That's exactly how I'm feeling.

230
00:08:24.638 --> 00:08:25.873
So what did you do?

231
00:08:25.973 --> 00:08:28.509
Well. we realized
she needed to be weaned.

232
00:08:28.609 --> 00:08:30.211
so for a time

233
00:08:30.311 --> 00:08:32.713
we brought a taste of
the asylum back to Woodstone.

234
00:08:32.813 --> 00:08:34.048
To help Mother go to sleep.

235
00:08:34.148 --> 00:08:35.383
my sister Margaret and I

236
00:08:35.483 --> 00:08:37.418
would wail psychotically
outside her door.

237
00:08:37.518 --> 00:08:39.220
Interesting. So you're
saying I should bring

238
00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:41.055
some of the basement upstairs.

239
00:08:41.155 --> 00:08:43.958
at least until I've weaned
myself of their ways.

240
00:08:44.058 --> 00:08:45.292
Indeed. Exactly.

241
00:08:45.393 --> 00:08:46.293
Genius.

242
00:08:46.394 --> 00:08:47.628
Thank you.

243
00:08:47.728 --> 00:08:49.563
Now. where was I? Oh. yes.

244
00:08:49.663 --> 00:08:53.401
Oh. it was a dangerous summer
for shellfish.

245
00:08:53.502 --> 00:08:55.736
<i>GARRETT:</i>
<i>I'm surprised</i>
<i>you wanted to borrow a DVD.</i>

246
00:08:55.836 --> 00:08:57.204
Don't y'all have
streaming over there?

247
00:08:57.304 --> 00:08:59.140
I'm more of
a physical media guy.

248
00:08:59.240 --> 00:09:02.443
Me. too. Though
I got burned bad by Betamax.

249
00:09:02.543 --> 00:09:04.078
How did VHS win?

250
00:09:04.178 --> 00:09:06.380
It's a slightly
inferior platform.

251
00:09:06.480 --> 00:09:07.948
Oh. there's
